         <abstract>
            <p>We show that the minimum period modul p of the Bell exponential integers is (p&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt; - 1)/(p - 1) for all primes &lt;latex&gt;$p &lt; 102$&lt;/latex&gt; and several larger p. Our proof of this result requires the primes factorization of these periods. For some primes p the factoring is aided by an algebraic formula called an Aurifeuillian factorization. We explain how the coefficients of the factors in these formulas may be computed.</p>
          </abstract>
